    "summary": "KEEP \"impels\" — Chinese is genuinely stronger in footnote",
    "content": "**KEEP \"impels.\"** The Chinese is genuinely different in the two places. 推动 (push/drive) in the footnote is stronger and more mechanical than 想要 (want to) in the body. The author chose different words deliberately — the footnote is explicating the structural role of 义 as a connecting force between feeling and action, where the stronger \"impels\" is appropriate. The body text is narrating the lived experience, where the softer \"moves me to want to\" fits. Harmonizing would erase a real distinction in the original."
  }
}
